      "lastUpdate": 1750687319294,
      "notes": "The Pen tool is crafted much like a vector drawing tool, allowing you to plot and shape your envelope with precision.\n\nWhen creating a new freeform clip, the Pen tool is automatically selected. In this tutorial navigate to the Tool bar and select the Pen icon.\n\n<p align=\"center\"> <img width=\"100%\" src=\"media://assets/pentoolbar.png\"/>\n\n/newpage\n\nTo switch between tools, use the Tool bar or keyboard shortcuts. Press Enter or Escape to exit the Pen tool.\n\n<p align=\"center\"> <img width=\"100%\" src=\"media://assets/shortcuts.png\"/>\n\n/newpage\nLet's start drawing!\n\nThe Pen tool starts at the origin (0.0). To change the initial value, move your cursor upward along the vertical axis.\n\nSet your first point at (0/0.4). Now move along the canvas and click to place breakpoints, this begins filling the envelope.\n\nTry to create a shape similar to the one shown below.\n\n<p align=\"center\"> <img width=\"100%\" src=\"media://assets/shape.png\"/>\n\n\n/newpage\n\n<b>Adding Points</b>\nMove across the canvas and click to add additional points.\n\n<b>Guidance</b>\nWhite guiding lines will appear to help you align new points in reference to previously placed ones.\n\n<b>Complete Envelope</b>\nPress Enter when you're done to complete the envelope.\n\n<b>Edit and Extend</b>\nYou can always return to your envelope to refine it by selecting the Pen tool again.\n\nAdd new points or adjust existing breakpoints as needed. To remove a point, select it and press Delete on your keyboard.\n\n"
    },
    {
